## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Scope

This ticket implements four security capabilities:

1. **Misconfiguration Scan** — Detect insecure configurations: debug mode enabled, permissive CORS, weak TLS, insecure cookies (20 sinks)
2. **Secrets Entropy Detection** — Find hardcoded secrets using Shannon entropy analysis + pattern matching
3. **SBOM Generation** — Generate CycloneDX Software Bill of Materials from lockfiles (8 formats)
4. **Dependency Audit** — Check dependencies against OSV vulnerability database
5. **SARIF Export** — Export all security findings in SARIF format for GitHub/GitLab integration

### 1.2 Out of Scope

* Runtime configuration scanning (only static code/config files)
* Secret rotation / remediation
* License compliance checking (future ticket)
* Dependency auto-update / PR creation
* Custom vulnerability database

### 1.3 Preliminary Requirements

* KSA-164: Control Flow + Data Flow Analysis (for misconfig detection in code)
* KSA-165: Injection Detection (shared pattern infrastructure)
* KSA-145: Tree-sitter Core (AST parsing)
* Network access for OSV API queries (dependency audit)

## 2. Business Requirements

### 2.1 High Level Process Map

This ticket provides “supply chain security” and “configuration security” capabilities: - Misconfig: scans code and config files for insecure settings - Secrets: finds accidentally committed credentials - SBOM: inventories all dependencies for compliance/audit - Dep Audit: checks inventory against known vulnerabilities - SARIF: standardized output for CI/CD integration

### 2.2 List of User Stories / Use Cases

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Story / Use Case | Priority | Source Ticket |
| 1 | As a security engineer, I want misconfiguration detected so that insecure settings are found before deployment | MUST HAVE | KSA-167 |
| 2 | As a security engineer, I want hardcoded secrets detected so that credentials don’t leak to repositories | MUST HAVE | KSA-167 |
| 3 | As a compliance officer, I want SBOM generated so that I have a complete dependency inventory | MUST HAVE | KSA-167 |
| 4 | As a developer, I want dependency vulnerabilities flagged so that I can update affected packages | SHOULD HAVE | KSA-167 |
| 5 | As a DevOps engineer, I want SARIF export so that findings integrate with GitHub/GitLab security dashboards | SHOULD HAVE | KSA-167 |

### 2.3 Details of User Stories

#### Business Flow

**Step 1:** Developer requests security scan (via MCP tool)

**Step 2:** Misconfig scanner checks code + config files against 20 sink patterns

**Step 3:** Secrets scanner analyzes strings for high entropy + known patterns

**Step 4:** SBOM generator reads lockfiles, produces CycloneDX inventory

**Step 5:** Dependency auditor queries OSV API with SBOM components

**Step 6:** All findings aggregated, exported as SARIF

**Step 7:** Results returned via MCP tool + SARIF file written

#### STORY 1: Misconfiguration Detection

As a security engineer, I want misconfiguration detected so that insecure settings are found before deployment.

**Requirement Details:**

**20 Misconfiguration Sinks:**

|  |  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Category | Pattern | CWE | Severity |
| 1 | Debug | DEBUG=True in production config | CWE-489 | High |
| 2 | Debug | Verbose error messages enabled | CWE-209 | Medium |
| 3 | Debug | Stack trace exposure in responses | CWE-497 | Medium |
| 4 | CORS | Access-Control-Allow-Origin: \* | CWE-942 | High |
| 5 | CORS | Credentials with wildcard origin | CWE-942 | Critical |
| 6 | CORS | Reflecting Origin header without validation | CWE-942 | High |
| 7 | TLS | TLS 1.0/1.1 enabled | CWE-326 | High |
| 8 | TLS | SSL verification disabled | CWE-295 | Critical |
| 9 | TLS | Self-signed cert in production | CWE-295 | Medium |
| 10 | Cookies | Missing Secure flag | CWE-614 | Medium |
| 11 | Cookies | Missing HttpOnly flag | CWE-1004 | Medium |
| 12 | Cookies | Missing SameSite attribute | CWE-1275 | Medium |
| 13 | Headers | Missing X-Frame-Options | CWE-1021 | Medium |
| 14 | Headers | Missing Content-Security-Policy | CWE-693 | Medium |
| 15 | Headers | Missing X-Content-Type-Options | CWE-16 | Low |
| 16 | Auth | Hardcoded credentials in config | CWE-798 | Critical |
| 17 | Auth | Default passwords not changed | CWE-1393 | High |
| 18 | Session | Session timeout too long (> 24h) | CWE-613 | Medium |
| 19 | Logging | Sensitive data in logs | CWE-532 | High |
| 20 | Crypto | Weak hash algorithm (MD5/SHA1 for security) | CWE-328 | High |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. All 20 misconfig patterns detected across config files and code
2. Scans: .env, .yml, .yaml, .json, .properties, .toml, .xml config files
3. Scans code for programmatic misconfigurations
4. Each finding includes CWE, severity, file location, remediation
5. False positive rate < 20% for config file patterns

#### STORY 2: Secrets Entropy Detection

As a security engineer, I want hardcoded secrets detected so that credentials don’t leak to repositories.

**Requirement Details:**

**Detection Methods:**

1. **Shannon Entropy** — Strings with entropy > 4.5 bits/char (high randomness = likely secret)
2. **Pattern Matching** — Known secret formats:
   * AWS keys: AKIA[0-9A-Z]{16}
   * GitHub tokens: ghp\_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}
   * JWT: eyJ[a-zA-Z0-9\_-]+\.eyJ[a-zA-Z0-9\_-]+\.[a-zA-Z0-9\_-]+
   * Private keys: -----BEGIN (RSA|EC|DSA) PRIVATE KEY-----
   * Generic API keys: (api[\_-]?key|secret|token|password)\s\*[:=]\s\*['"][^'"]{8,}['"]
3. **Context Analysis** — Variable name suggests secret (password, secret, token, api\_key)

**Exclusions (reduce false positives):** - Test files (configurable) - Example/placeholder values (e.g., “your-api-key-here”) - Hash constants (known library hashes) - UUIDs (format matches but not secrets)

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Detects high-entropy strings (Shannon > 4.5) in source code
2. Detects known secret patterns (AWS, GitHub, JWT, etc.)
3. Context-aware: variable name “password” with literal value = finding
4. Excludes test files and placeholder values
5. Reports secret type, location, and remediation

#### STORY 3: SBOM Generation (CycloneDX)

As a compliance officer, I want SBOM generated so that I have a complete dependency inventory.

**Requirement Details:**

**Supported Lockfile Formats (8):**

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Format | Language | File |
| 1 | npm | JavaScript/TypeScript | package-lock.json, yarn.lock, pnpm-lock.yaml |
| 2 | pip | Python | requirements.txt, Pipfile.lock, poetry.lock |
| 3 | Maven | Java/Kotlin | pom.xml (resolved), gradle.lockfile |
| 4 | Go | Go | go.sum |
| 5 | Cargo | Rust | Cargo.lock |
| 6 | Composer | PHP | composer.lock |
| 7 | Gems | Ruby | Gemfile.lock |
| 8 | NuGet | C#/.NET | packages.lock.json |

**Output Format:** CycloneDX 1.5 JSON

**SBOM Fields per Component:** - name, version, purl (Package URL) - license (if available from lockfile) - hash (integrity hash from lockfile) - scope (runtime/dev)

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Parses all 8 lockfile formats correctly
2. Generates valid CycloneDX 1.5 JSON
3. Includes transitive dependencies (from lockfiles)
4. Distinguishes runtime vs dev dependencies
5. SBOM validates against CycloneDX schema

#### STORY 4: Dependency Audit (OSV)

As a developer, I want dependency vulnerabilities flagged so that I can update affected packages.

**Requirement Details:**

1. Take SBOM components (from Story 3)
2. Query OSV.dev API for known vulnerabilities
3. Match by package name + version range
4. Report: CVE ID, severity (CVSS), affected versions, fixed version
5. Cache results (TTL: 24h) to avoid repeated API calls

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Queries OSV API for all SBOM components
2. Reports CVE/GHSA IDs with severity scores
3. Shows which version fixes the vulnerability
4. Caches results to reduce API calls
5. Works offline with cached data (stale but available)

#### STORY 5: SARIF Export

As a DevOps engineer, I want SARIF export so that findings integrate with GitHub/GitLab security dashboards.

**Requirement Details:**

1. Export ALL security findings (misconfig + secrets + injection + SSRF/IDOR + dep audit) as SARIF 2.1.0
2. SARIF includes: tool info, rules, results with locations, severity levels
3. Compatible with GitHub Code Scanning and GitLab SAST
4. One SARIF file per scan run

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Valid SARIF 2.1.0 output
2. All finding types included in single SARIF file
3. GitHub Code Scanning accepts and displays results
4. Rule IDs map to CWE numbers
5. Locations include file path, line, column

